<div id=3D"outline-container-5" class=3D"outline-2">
<h2 id=3D"5">OCaml library for Timeplus Proton timeseries streaming databas=
e</h2>
<div class=3D"outline-text-2" id=3D"text-5">
<p>
Archive: <a href=3D"https://discuss.ocaml.org/t/ann-ocaml-library-for-timep=
lus-proton-timeseries-streaming-database/17440/1">https://discuss.ocaml.org=
/t/ann-ocaml-library-for-timeplus-proton-timeseries-streaming-database/1744=
0/1</a>
</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"outline-container-org9ae058c" class=3D"outline-3">
<h3 id=3D"org9ae058c">Michael Freeman announced</h3>
<div class=3D"outline-text-3" id=3D"text-org9ae058c">
<p>
A high-performance, feature-rich OCaml driver for <a href=3D"https://timepl=
us.com/">Timeplus Proton</a> - the streaming database built on ClickHouse.
</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"outline-container-org324204d" class=3D"outline-4">
<h4 id=3D"org324204d"><b>Features</b></h4>
<div class=3D"outline-text-4" id=3D"text-org324204d">
<ul class=3D"org-ul">
<li><b>Streaming Queries</b> - Process large datasets with constant memory =
usage</li>
<li><b>Async Inserts</b> - High-throughput data ingestion with automatic ba=
tching</li>
<li><b>Compression</b> - LZ4 and ZSTD support for reduced network overhead<=
/li>
<li><b>TLS Security</b> - Secure connections with certificate validation</l=
i>
<li><b>Connection Pooling</b> - Efficient resource management for high-conc=
urrency applications</li>
<li><b>Rich Data Types</b> - Full support for ClickHouse types including Ar=
rays, Maps, Enums, DateTime64</li>
<li><b>Idiomatic OCaml</b> - Functional API leveraging OCaml's strengths</l=
i>
</ul>

<p>
<a href=3D"https://github.com/mfreeman451/proton-ocaml-driver">https://gith=
ub.com/mfreeman451/proton-ocaml-driver</a>
</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div id=3D"outline-container-6" class=3D"outline-2">
<h2 id=3D"6">Book draft: "Control structures in programming languages"</h2>
<div class=3D"outline-text-2" id=3D"text-6">
<p>
Archive: <a href=3D"https://discuss.ocaml.org/t/book-draft-control-structur=
es-in-programming-languages/17443/1">https://discuss.ocaml.org/t/book-draft=
-control-structures-in-programming-languages/17443/1</a>
</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"outline-container-orga070dd5" class=3D"outline-3">
<h3 id=3D"orga070dd5">Xavier Leroy announced</h3>
<div class=3D"outline-text-3" id=3D"text-orga070dd5">
<p>
I am happy to announce that a draft of my upcoming book "Control structures=
 in programming languages: from goto to algebraic effects" is now available=
 at <a href=3D"https://xavierleroy.org/control-structures">https://xavierle=
roy.org/control-structures</a> .
</p>

<p>
The book compares several programming languages from the standpoint of cont=
rol structures.  OCaml is used intensively to discuss control in functional=
 programming, including continuation-passing style, control operators, exce=
ptions, user-defined effects and effect handlers, with many examples that I=
 hope you'll like.
</p>

<p>
The book also discusses in depth a number of questions that are often raise=
d in this forum, such as the theory and practice of algebraic effects and h=
andlers, and the static checking of exceptions and effects.
</p>

<p>
Enjoy!
</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div id=3D"outline-container-7" class=3D"outline-2">
<h2 id=3D"7">oplot 0.85 - mathematical plotter</h2>
<div class=3D"outline-text-2" id=3D"text-7">
<p>
Archive: <a href=3D"https://discuss.ocaml.org/t/ann-oplot-0-85-mathematical=
-plotter/17444/1">https://discuss.ocaml.org/t/ann-oplot-0-85-mathematical-p=
lotter/17444/1</a>
</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"outline-container-org8171275" class=3D"outline-3">
<h3 id=3D"org8171275">sanette announced</h3>
<div class=3D"outline-text-3" id=3D"text-org8171275">
<p>
Hello=20
</p>

<p>
I=E2=80=99m happy to announce a new version of <a href=3D"https://github.co=
m/sanette/oplot">oplot</a>, a library for plotting mathematical functions, =
using openGL by default for fast rendering and animations, but also providi=
ng high quality vector graphics exports.
</p>

<p>
This version has a new feature that math lovers will appreciate: <code>impl=
icit_curve</code> plotting!
</p>

<p>
For instance do you want to know what the solutions to the equation (x=C2=
=B2+y=C2=B2-1)=C2=B3 - x=C2=B2 y=C2=B3 =3D 0 look like?
</p>

<p>
Here is the result:
</p>


<div id=3D"org46570d4" class=3D"figure">
<p><img src=3D"https://us1.discourse-cdn.com/flex020/uploads/ocaml/optimize=
d/2X/0/00fbc53496cd6a8e5b9fb37807e9f5243b79e75e_2_1222x1000.png" alt=3D"00f=
bc53496cd6a8e5b9fb37807e9f5243b79e75e_2_1222x1000.png" width=3D"80%" />
</p>
</div>

<p>
If you already dug into the problem of plotting implicit curves you know th=
at it=E2=80=99s sometimes very difficult to localize in advance the various=
 singularities of the curve. <code>oplot</code> gives you 3 ways of tuning =
the computation: grid size, recursive grid size for subsampling where the c=
urvature of the curve seems high, and control over the iterations of the Ne=
wton method. There is also a pole detection, where the function changes sig=
n but probably still doesn=E2=80=99t have a zero there. You can obtain debu=
g information for any curve, for instance here you see the default paramete=
rs automatically detected for the above curve: initial grid (green) and sub=
sampling (cyan):
</p>


<div id=3D"org3ca459c" class=3D"figure">
<p><img src=3D"https://us1.discourse-cdn.com/flex020/uploads/ocaml/optimize=
d/2X/1/1edb6f547feb24bd42aad4f21d0bb20c2455d684_2_1222x1000.png" alt=3D"1ed=
b6f547feb24bd42aad4f21d0bb20c2455d684_2_1222x1000.png" width=3D"80%" />
</p>
</div>

<p>
<code>oplot</code> is available in opam, doc is <a href=3D"https://sanette.=
github.io/oplot/oplot/Oplot/index.html">here</a>.
</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div id=3D"outline-container-8" class=3D"outline-2">
<h2 id=3D"8">QCheck 0.27</h2>
<div class=3D"outline-text-2" id=3D"text-8">
<p>
Archive: <a href=3D"https://discuss.ocaml.org/t/ann-qcheck-0-24/16198/4">ht=
tps://discuss.ocaml.org/t/ann-qcheck-0-24/16198/4</a>
</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"outline-container-orgcc60338" class=3D"outline-3">
<h3 id=3D"orgcc60338">Jan Midtgaard announced</h3>
<div class=3D"outline-text-3" id=3D"text-orgcc60338">
<p>
QCheck 0.27 is now available from the opam repository :partying_face:
</p>

<p>
<a href=3D"https://github.com/c-cube/qcheck/releases/tag/v0.27">https://git=
hub.com/c-cube/qcheck/releases/tag/v0.27</a>
</p>

<p>
The 0.27 release is focused on improving the <code>float</code> shrinking s=
upport and also contains a small patch to make the package compile with OxC=
aml:
</p>
<ul class=3D"org-ul">
<li>Add <code>QCheck.Shrink.float</code> and enable shrinking for <code>QCh=
eck.float</code></li>
<li>Add <code>QCheck.Shrink.float_bound</code> and enable shrinking for <co=
de>QCheck.float_bound_inclusive</code> and <code>QCheck.float_bound_exclusi=
ve</code></li>
<li>Add <code>QCheck.Shrink.float_range</code> and enable shrinking for <co=
de>QCheck.float_range</code></li>
<li>Enable shrinking for <code>QCheck.{pos_float,neg_float,exponential}</co=
de></li>
<li>Patch <code>QCheck.Print.float</code> and <code>QCheck2.Print.float</co=
de> to print negative nans consistently as "-nan" also on Windows and macOS=
, and correct documentation for <code>QCheck.{float,pos_float,neg_float}</c=
ode> in that they may produce ~nan~s since #350 from 0.26</li>
<li>Eta-expand a couple of partial application to compile under OxCaml</li>
</ul>

<p>
Happy testing! :smiley:
</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div id=3D"outline-container-9" class=3D"outline-2">
<h2 id=3D"9">Bytesrw 0.3.0 =E2=80=93 The cryptographic edition</h2>
<div class=3D"outline-text-2" id=3D"text-9">
<p>
Archive: <a href=3D"https://discuss.ocaml.org/t/ann-bytesrw-0-3-0-the-crypt=
ographic-edition/17450/1">https://discuss.ocaml.org/t/ann-bytesrw-0-3-0-the=
-cryptographic-edition/17450/1</a>
</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"outline-container-orgdcfd6b1" class=3D"outline-3">
<h3 id=3D"orgdcfd6b1">Daniel B=C3=BCnzli announced</h3>
<div class=3D"outline-text-3" id=3D"text-orgdcfd6b1">
<p>
Hello,=20
</p>

<p>
It's my pleasure to announce a new release of the <a href=3D"https://errati=
que.ch/software/bytesrw">bytesrw</a> set of ISC licensed libraries.
</p>

<blockquote>
<p>
Bytesrw extends the OCaml Bytes module with composable, memory efficient,  =
byte stream readers and writers compatible with effect-based concurrency.
</p>

<p>
Optional support for compressed, hashed and encrypted bytes depend, at your=
 wish, on the C <code>zlib</code>, <code>libzstd</code>, <code>blake3</code=
>, <code>libmd</code>, <code>xxhash</code> and  <code>mbedtls</code> librar=
ies.
</p>
</blockquote>

<p>
This release adds optional libraries to support for <code>SHA-3</code> hash=
es, cryptographically secure pseudo-random bytes streams, TLS encrypted byt=
e stream and low-level support for cryptographic operations on slices:
</p>

<ul class=3D"org-ul">
<li><a href=3D"https://erratique.ch/software/bytesrw/doc/Bytesrw_sysrandom/=
index.html"><code>Bytesrw_sysrandom</code></a> provides pseudorandom byte s=
treams and entropy directly sourced from your operating system primitives.<=
/li>

<li><a href=3D"https://erratique.ch/software/bytesrw/doc/Bytesrw_crypto/Psa=
/index.html"><code>Bytesrw_crypto.Psa</code></a> provides low-level cryptog=
raphic operations on byte slices via thin and safe bindings to the <a href=
=3D"https://github.com/Mbed-TLS/TF-PSA-Crypto">TF-PSA-Crypto</a> C library =
distributed with Mbed TLS. This library is an implementation of the <a href=
=3D"https://arm-software.github.io/psa-api/crypto/1.2/">PSA Crypto API Spec=
ification</a>. Its design is particularly suited if you care about key mate=
riel not being seen by the OCaml GC (implementations also allow further deg=
rees of isolation as can be read in the API's <a href=3D"https://arm-softwa=
re.github.io/psa-api/crypto/1.2/overview/goals.html">design goals</a>). Bes=
ides the API is nicely and thoroughly documented. It is quite bureaucratic =
to use but that's what you likely want from a cryptographic library (e.g. k=
ey usages have to be declared upfront and are checked at runtime by cryptog=
raphic operations).</li>

<li><a href=3D"https://erratique.ch/software/bytesrw/doc/Bytesrw_crypto/ind=
ex.html"><code>Bytesrw_crypto</code></a> (will) provides a few higher-level=
 operations implemented over PSA. The module is rather shallow at the momen=
t, more will be added in the future as we abstract over our usage of PSA Cr=
ypto. For now it mostly contains an API to access the hashes provided by PS=
A Crypto in the way other <code>bytesrw</code> hashing modules expose their=
 hashing service. This notably provides the <code>SHA-3</code> family of ha=
shes which were not previously available in the set of optional <code>bytes=
rw</code> libraries.</li>

<li><a href=3D"https://erratique.ch/software/bytesrw/doc/Bytesrw_tls/index.=
html"><code>Bytesrw_tls</code></a> provides support for TLS encrypted strea=
ms and the needed X.509 certificate management (including system lookups fo=
r trusted CAs). The backend is provided by the <a href=3D"https://www.trust=
edfirmware.org/projects/mbed-tls/">Mbed TLS</a> C library. For now these st=
reams are instantied over blocking fds, but this restriction will be lifted=
 in the future. I also added a little tool called <code>certown</code> whic=
h you may find handy for dealing with certificates for localhost when you d=
evelop servers.</li>
</ul>

<p>
Note that the binding to PSA cryptography has been used to implement a few =
things (e.g. the horrific passkeys specification) but has not run in produc=
tion yet. However the binding is pleasantly unsophisticated, the underlying=
 C API is straightforward to bind to.
</p>

<p>
See the <a href=3D"https://github.com/dbuenzli/bytesrw/blob/main/CHANGES.md=
#v030-2025-11-04-zagreb">release notes</a> for details about other changes.
</p>

<p>
This release was made possible thanks to a grant from the <a href=3D"https:=
//ocaml-sf.org/">OCaml software foundation</a> and to my <a href=3D"https:/=
/github.com/sponsors/dbuenzli">donors</a>.
</p>

<ul class=3D"org-ul">
<li>Homepage: <a href=3D"https://erratique.ch/software/bytesrw">https://err=
atique.ch/software/bytesrw</a></li>
<li>Docs: <a href=3D"https://erratique.ch/software/bytesrw/doc">https://err=
atique.ch/software/bytesrw/doc</a> (or <code>odig doc bytesrw</code>)</li>
<li>Install: <code>opam install bytesrw conf-=E2=80=A6</code> (<a href=3D"h=
ttps://github.com/ocaml/opam-repository/pull/28836">opam pr</a>)</li>
</ul>

<p>
&mdash;
</p>

<p>
P.S. Libraries that depend on Mbed TLS need the recent 4.0.0 version which =
is quite fresh and may take a bit of time to trickle in system package mana=
gers. If you trust me you can use my
<a href=3D"https://github.com/dbuenzli/distrib-crutch.opam">distribution cr=
utch</a> opam repository to install it.
</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
